                                    <!-- FAQ Section for AEO -->
                                    <div class="faq-section" style="margin-top: 40px;">
                                        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                                        <h3>How much does it cost to build a grocery delivery app like Blinkit or Zepto?</h3>
                                        <p>MVP single-dark-store grocery app: &#8377;9L–&#8377;14L over 6–8 weeks. Growth multi-dark-store one-city build: &#8377;22L–&#8377;32L over 14–18 weeks. Enterprise multi-city build with AI dispatch and sub-15-min promise: &#8377;45L+. The cost step-up over normal marketplace builds is the dispatch engine, picker workflow and inventory sync layer.</p>
                                        <h3>How many SKUs does a quick-commerce dark store carry?</h3>
                                        <p>A typical 2,000 sq ft dark store carries 1,500–3,000 SKUs covering ~80% of basket. Zepto and Blinkit run 2,500–3,500 SKU dark stores in metro locations. Tier-2 cities profitable at 1,200–2,000 SKUs. The 80/20 rule applies: half the basket comes from 200–300 SKUs.</p>
                                        <h3>What's a realistic delivery promise — 10, 15 or 30 minutes?</h3>
                                        <p>10 minutes works in dense metro suburbs with one dark store per 1.5 km. 15 minutes is the safe default for most metro deployments. 30 minutes covers Tier-2/3 expansion. Over-promising breaks customer trust faster than slightly slower delivery.</p>
                                        <h3>How do I onboard riders for a quick-commerce app?</h3>
                                        <p>Start with 30–50 riders per dark store. Mix of full-time and gig (60/40 typical). Pay above Zomato/Swiggy base rates for the first 90 days to build supply density. Provide branded jackets and bags — riders treat branded gigs as more legitimate.</p>
                                        <h3>Should I build it myself or buy a white-label q-commerce platform?</h3>
                                        <p>White-label saves 4–6 months for testing demand. But the dispatch algorithm, surge engine, and dark-store ops layer are usually limited or generic — once you cross 200 orders/day per store, white-label friction will force a custom rebuild. Most funded q-commerce startups go custom by month 9.</p>
